Let $n+2005 = p_1^{a_1}p_2^{a_2}...p_k^{a_k}$ where $p_ i$ are primer and $a_ i$ are positive integers. The number of positive factors is $(a_1+1)(a_2+1)...(a_k+1)$. Rewrite as $f_1 f_2...f_k=21$. The number of ways to factorize 21 is 6:$$ 1\times21, 3\times7, 1\times3\times7, 1\times1\times1\times1\times1\times 21, 1\times1\times1\times3\times1\times7,1\times1\times1\times1\times3\times7.$$Consider the factorization $p_1^{20}p_2^{20}$, we get the number $n=78066916\times20-2005=1561316375$ This factorization corresponds to the decomposition $21=21\times 1$.</think> <answer>When k=4 the only x-solution is x=1;
